<div id="review_4328989224" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4328989224" />
    <a title="TheBookWarren" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24831615-thebookwarren"><img alt="TheBookWarren" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1630126428p2/24831615.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4328989224?book_show_action=true">Nov 08, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="TheBookWarren" class="user" itemprop="url" name="TheBookWarren" href="/user/show/24831615-thebookwarren">TheBookWarren</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781848453036" href="/book/show/23002832-the-returned">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24831615-thebookwarren?shelf=fiction-contemporary-drama">fiction-contemporary-drama</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24831615-thebookwarren?shelf=rcmnd-to-me-by-multiple-sources">rcmnd-to-me-by-multiple-sources</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24831615-thebookwarren?shelf=mystery-intrigue-puzzler">mystery-intrigue-puzzler</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24831615-thebookwarren?shelf=psychological-thrillers">psychological-thrillers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4328989224" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5994339104510596985">2.75 Stars — (Rnd ⬆️) — The Returned has a disturbed &amp; somewhat deep-seeded-psychopathy to its narrative, that somehow feels eerily familiar to anyone whom picks it up. Whether it’s on a conscious level or subliminal, it always seems to be there! Crowd-paranoia? Shared fears are nothing new, especially one that is at the base level of consciousness. But what’s not instantly clear is whether an irrational fear — of a long lost loved one unexplainably and inexplicably return — creates that negatin</span>
  <span id="freeText5994339104510596985" style="display:none">2.75 Stars — (Rnd ⬆️) — The Returned has a disturbed &amp; somewhat deep-seeded-psychopathy to its narrative, that somehow feels eerily familiar to anyone whom picks it up. Whether it’s on a conscious level or subliminal, it always seems to be there! Crowd-paranoia? Shared fears are nothing new, especially one that is at the base level of consciousness. But what’s not instantly clear is whether an irrational fear — of a long lost loved one unexplainably and inexplicably return — creates that negating emotive vibe through the supernatural elements of it being illogical or is it a plain old matter of it being indubitably morose?<br /><br />Whatever the answer… Here, what beguns as a promising narrative with what feels like a solid if not at times rushed or maybe over engineered flow and plot, eventually morphs or eventuates into more of a novelty-gimmick in the important ‘middle’ before again finding its groove again in the final 30 pages.<br /><br />More writes well enough and clearly has a skill-set to match many writers today. Parts of this are as edgy as a non-toddler proofed kitchen, others are more akin to the amount of edginess found in a sack of spuds! But the tension built through a long-standing paranoid ache pulsates (mostly) throughout as our returning dead remain both mysterious &amp; sketchy to all apart from select few in which whom love them the most and I remained guessing whether it was a sign of the end or a sign of a delusion or something else entirely. The constant guessing and speculative force remained alluring if lacking in nuance. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5994339104510596985" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


